03843nam a22005055i 9780822395447DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20122012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223954477 a10.1515/97808223954472doi  a(DE-B1597)554401  a(OCoLC)1202624874  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0100002bisacsh1 aChen, Mel Y., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAnimacies :bBiopolitics, Racial Mattering, and Queer Affect /cMel Y. Chen. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b20 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerverse Modernities: A Series Edited by Jack Halberstam and Lisa Lowe00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Animating Animacy -- t1. Language and Mattering Humans -- t2. Queer Animation -- t3. Queer Animality -- t4. Animals, Sex, and Transsubstantiation -- t5. Lead's Racial Matters -- t6. Following Mercurial Affect -- tAfterword: The Spill and the Sea -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Animacies, Mel Y. Chen draws on recent debates about sexuality, race, and affect to examine how matter that is considered insensate, immobile, or deathly animates cultural lives. Toward that end, Chen investigates the blurry division between the living and the dead, or that which is beyond the human or animal. Within the field of linguistics, animacy has been described variously as a quality of agency, awareness, mobility, sentience, or liveness. Chen turns to cognitive linguistics to stress how language habitually differentiates the animate and the inanimate. Expanding this construct, Chen argues that animacy undergirds much that is pressing and indeed volatile in contemporary culture, from animal rights debates to biosecurity concerns.Chen's book is the first to bring the concept of animacy together with queer of color scholarship, critical animal studies, and disability theory. Through analyses of dehumanizing insults, the meanings of queerness, animal protagonists in recent Asian/American art and film, the lead in toys panic in 2007, and the social lives of environmental illness, Animacies illuminates a hierarchical politics infused by race, sexuality, and ability. In this groundbreaking book, Chen rethinks the criteria governing agency and receptivity, health and toxicity, productivity and stillness-and demonstrates how attention to the affective charge of matter challenges commonsense orderings of the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822395447zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822395447423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822395447.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles